Introduction to Paired-Sample T-Test.


    Paired-Sample T-Test:
  • Is used to determine if the mean difference between paired observations is statistically significantly different from zero.

  • Paired-Sample T-Test can also be used when your study has two groups of participants that have been paired on one or more characteristics, and tested as one dependent variable.

  • Paired-Sample T-Test is also known as:
    • Dependent t-test
    • Repeated measures t-test
    • Paired t-test

  • A t test is used to determine if there is a meaningful difference between groups. It lets you know if those differences could have happened by chance.

    Example
    • Case Determine if the mean difference in a muscle density before and after a twelve week muscle hypertrophy exercise regimen.
    • Dependent Variable Muscle Density.
    • Independent Variable Two related groups would be before and after muscle hypertrophy exercise regimen.
    • Null Hypothesis \(H_{0} \): The difference in the mean muscle density between the before and after groups is zero.
    • Alternative Hypothesis \(H_{A} \): The difference in the mean muscle density between the before and after groups is not zero.


Discuss the Assumptions for the Paired-Sample T-Test.


    Assumptions

    In order to run this test, these assumptions must be considered. Failure to consider these assumptions can result in misleading and inaccurate conclusions.


    1. You have one dependent variable that is measured on the continuous scale (ratio or interval).

    2. You have one independent variable that consists of two categorical, related or matched groups.
      Related Groups: mean that the two groups are not independent.

    3. There should be no significant outliers in both groups. Outliers are extreme data points within your sample that do no follow the pattern of the other data.

    4. The distribution of the differences of the dependent variable between the two related groups should be approximately normally distributed.



Mathematics of Paired-Sample T-Test.


    The t-test statistic
  • The test statistics for the paired-sample t-test follows the same formula as the one sample t-test and is expressed as:

    \[t = \frac{\bar{X}_{diff} - 0}{S_{\bar{X}}} \]

  • where \(S_{\bar{X}}\) is expresse as:

    \[S_{\bar{X}} = \frac{s_{diff}}{\sqrt{n}} \]

  • \(\bar{X}_{diff} \) is the mean of the difference between the groups.

  • \(s_{diff} \) is the standard deviation of the difference between the groups.

  • The degree of freedom \(df = n - 1 \) where n is the total number of pairs.

  • Once the test statistic is calculated, the t-test table needs to be consulted to obtain the critical value for the Student's t-distribution corresponding to the \(\alpha \) level of significance, typically 0.05, 0.01, or 0.001. The degree of freedom (df) must be used in the table to get the critical value.

  • The confidence interval around the difference in the means is expressed as:

    \[\bar{d} = t_{(n-1,\ two-sided\ \alpha)}(\frac{s_{d}}{\sqrt{n}}) \]

    Critical Region
  • The critical region is the region of values that corresponds to the rejection of the null hypothesis at some chosen probability level (see plot below).

  • The following steps are involved in the hypothesis testing process.

    1. Specify the null \(H_{0} \) and alternate hypothesis \(H_{A} \).

    2. Specify the level of significance \(\alpha \).

    3. Calculate the test statistic.

    4. Determine the critical value using the test statistic value, the degrees of freedom value, and the t-test table.

    5. If the the absolute value of the t-test statistic \(|t|\) is greater than the critical value, then the difference between the paired groups is significantly different.

# Example
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from scipy.stats import norm

n = 20
t = np.arange(-3, 3, 0.1)
t_val = -6.7
T_pos = 2.093 # upper-tailed test where alpha = 0.05
T_neg = -2.093 # lower-tailed test where alpha = 0.05

plt.figure(figsize=(15,5)) # figure size
plt.plot(t, norm.pdf(t)) # plots the z curve using normal probability distribution
# fills in area where Z-test is 0.05 and above
plt.fill_between(t[t>T_pos], norm.pdf(t[t>T_pos]), color="red") # upper tail
plt.fill_between(t[t<T_neg], norm.pdf(t[t<T_neg]), color="red") # lower tail

# Plots area where Null Hypothesis is accepted
plt.text(-0.5, 0.02, r'Accept $H_{0}:\ p\ value > \alpha\ (0.05)$', fontsize=10)
plt.text(-0.3, 0.17, r'1 - $\alpha$ = 0.95', fontsize=10) # labels region where Null is accepted

# Draws dash line in region where null is accepted
plt.arrow(x=t[t>T_pos][0], y=0, dx=(t[t<T_neg][-1]-t[t>T_pos][0]), dy=0, shape='full', head_length= 0, head_width=0, length_includes_head=False, linestyle='--')

# Plots area where Null Hypothesis should be rejected

# vertical lines that indicate where to reject and accept null hypothesis
plt.vlines(t[t<T_neg][-1], 0, 0.10, colors="black", linestyle="dashed") # lower tail critical vertical line
plt.vlines(t[t>T_pos][0], 0, 0.10, colors="black", linestyle="dashed")  # upper tail critical vertical line

# Vertical line for test
plt.vlines(t_val, 0, 0.10, colors="green", linestyle="dashed")  # upper tail critical vertical line
plt.text(t_val, 0.10, r'$Reject H_{0}: t = -6.7 $' '\n' r'$ t< t statistic -2.093, \alpha = 0.05$', fontsize=10)

# Text that indicates where to reject
plt.text(T_pos, 0.12, r'Reject $H_{0}$:''\n'r'$p\ value < \alpha\ (0.05)$', fontsize=10)
plt.text(-3, 0.12, r'Reject $H_{0}$:''\n'r'$p\ value < \alpha\ (0.05)$', fontsize=10)
plt.text(T_pos, 0.17, r'$\alpha$ = 0.05, t-test = 2.048', fontsize=10)
plt.text(-3, 0.17, r'$\alpha$ = 0.05, t-test = -2.048', fontsize=10)

# Horizontal red arrowy that indicate direction to reject
plt.arrow(x=t[t<T_neg][-1], y=0.10, dx=-1, dy=0, shape='full', head_length= 0.05, head_width=0.01, length_includes_head=True, color="red", linestyle='--')
plt.arrow(x=t[t>T_pos][0], y=0.10, dx=1, dy=0, shape='full', head_length= 0.05, head_width=0.01, length_includes_head=True, color="red", linestyle='--')

# title for plot with details on test
plt.title('Example Critical Regions for Independent Sample t-test' '\n' r'$\alpha = 0.05,\ t \pm 2.093, \ df=19, n=20$')
plt.show()


Comments

  • The areas under the curve in red correspond to the critical regions of the test.
  • In this example (green vertical dash line) our test statistic is significantly less than the lower tail, and we should then reject the null hypothesis.


Demonstrate how perform a Paired-Sample T-Test using SPSS.

    Steps

  1. Review case and organize variables, and set-up hypothesis.

  2. Set up data in SPSS.

  3. Confirm data does not violate assumptions.

  4. Carry out Paired-Sample T-Test.

  5. Interpret Results.

  6. Calculate Effect Size.

Review case and organize variables, and set-up hypothesis


  • Project: A supplement company wants to test a new formulation of their pre-workout beverage to determine if it improves the running performance. They have a standard pre-workout formulation with electrolytes and caffeine, but want to test a new mixture that contains carbohydrates.

  • Sample size: A total of 20 participants were recruited to perform two trials in which they had to run as far as possible for 1 hour on a treadmill. In one trial they drank the pre-workout beverage only and the distance ran was measured. In the second trial, they drank the pre-workout with carbohydrates, and the distance ran was also measured..

  • Independent Variable: The pre-workout beverage type.

  • Dependent Variable: The distance ran.

  • Goal: Determine if the new formulation leads to difference in performance compared to the standard pre-workout drink.

  • The Null hypothesis \(H_{0}: \mu_{diff} = 0 \): The mean difference between the paired values is zero.

  • The Alternative hypothesis \(H_{A}: \mu_{diff} \neq 0 \): The mean difference between the paired values is not zero.

  • The Level of Significance \(\alpha = 0.05\).

Set up data in SPSS


    SPSS Variable View
  • Either import or manually input data for the variables of interest.

    SPSS Data View
  • There are 20 total instances of data, with two columns representing the distance ran after having either the standard pre-workout or the pre-workout drink with carbohydrates.

    Add a new feature to the data, the difference between the paired values.
  • In a paired-samples t-test, we the assumption of normality and the presence of no outliers on the differences between the paired-values, not the values of the paired groups themselves. So we must add this feature to the data frame.

  • Steps: Transform > Compute Variable > In Compute Variable dialogue box > Type "Difference" in Target Variable text field > In Numeric Expression text box Preworkout_carbs - preworkout > OK button. These steps will add a new column in the table. We can then test the assumptions for a Paired-Sample T-Test.

Confirm data does not violate assumptions


    Why confirm assumptions?
  • A critical part of the process is confirming that the data we want to analyze meets the requirements for this model.

  • If the data does not meet the models requirements, then it will provide misleading and inaccurate results.

  1. Study design contains a continuous dependent variable \(\checkmark \)
    • The difference between groups takes on data that is continuous.
    • The data meets the first assumption for continuous dependent variable.

  2. Independent variable is categorical with two related groups. \(\checkmark \)
    • In this study, our independent variable is the supplement beverage, we have two types and we do have related groups.
    • The related groups refer to participants that have measurements for both independent variable. We have distance ran for each individual with the carb loaded supplement, and without the carb loaded supplement.
    • The data meets the second assumption for an independent categorical variable with two categories with related groups.

  3. There should be no significant outliers in the difference between the two related groups. \(\checkmark \)
    • Method used Boxplot Method: Analyze > Descriptive Statistics > Explore
    • Explore Dialogue box: Web landing to Factor list > Engagement to Dependent list > Click Plots
    • Explore: Plots Dialogue box: Check normality plots with tests > Un check stem-and-leaf in descriptive area > Click Continue > Return to Explore Dialogue box > Click OK
    • The box plot generated does not indicate that there is a data point for difference between the paired group that is 1.5 box-lengths from the edge of their box.
    • The data meets the assumption for not significant outliers for both groups.

  4. The distribution of the difference in the dependent variable between the two related groups is approximately normally distributed for each group of the independent variable. \(\checkmark \)
    • Method used Shapiro-Wilk Test: Steps above will produce the shapiro-wilk test in the output.
    • The Shapiro-Wilk Test test for normality.
    • If \(p-value < \alpha (0.05)\ Reject\ H_{0} \) Data is not normally distributed, Independent-sample t-test is not the best test to use for this study design. Suggest using the Mann-Whitney U test.
    • If \(p-value > \alpha (0.05)\ Accept\ H_{0} \) Data is normally distributed, Independent-sample t-test can be used for this study design.
    • The p-value for the shapiro-wil test is 0.780 which is greater than the level of significance 0.05. We accept the null hypothesis that the data comes from a normal distribution.
    • A Normal Q-Q plot was also generated, to evaluate normality for the difference between the distance ran, and the data points align along the diagonal line, which provides evidence for normality.
    • The data meets the third assumption for normality. The difference between the distance ran in the pre workout only and pre workout with carbohydrates were normally distributed, as assessed by Shapiro-Wilk's test (p = .780).
    • If the data was not normally distributed, then a nonparametric test such as the Wilcoxon signed-rank test or sign test would need to be considered.

    Paired sample statistics Preworkout with carb vs Preworkout.
  • The mean difference for both groups is 11.3 and 11.2 respectively.

  • The standard deviation is 0.71 and 0.73 respectively.

  • Data are mean standard deviation, unless otherwise stated. Participants ran further when imbibing the carbohydrate-preworkout drink (11.302 0.714 km) as opposed to the preworkout-only drink (11.167 0.726 km).
    Paired Samples Test
  • The mean difference is 0.1355 with a confidence interval of the difference between 0.09 and 0.18.

  • The p-value for the difference is less than 0.001.

  • The carbohydrate-preworkout drink elicited an increase of 0.136 (95% CI, 0.091 to 0.180) km in the distance run in one hour compared to a preworkout-only drink.

Interpret Results.


    Paired Sample Test
  • The carbohydrate-preworkout drink elicited a statistically significant increase in distance run in one hours compared to a preworkout-only drink, \(t(19) = 6.352, p < .0005\).

  • Recommendation: Recommend the new preworkout formulation as a performance enhancement supplement for runners.

Calculate the effect size using Cohen's d.


    Effect size
  • The effect size is a method used to express the magnitude of the difference observed with the t-test.

  • The Cohen's D Formula is a commonly used method to determine the magnitude (effect size) of the difference and is expressed:

    \[d = \frac{M}{SD} \]
    where \(M \) is the mean difference between the the related group

    \(SD \) is the standard deviation of this difference

  • Cohen's D can be calculated by using the group statistics table that is outputted by SPSS during this procedure.

  • SPSS does produce Cohen's d test in the Independent Sample Effect Size table. This is in the Point Estimate column for the Cohen's d row (illustrated below).

  • The effect size in this example: \[d = \frac{M}{SD} = \frac{0.13550}{0.09539} = 1.42 \]

  • The effect size can be determined by comparing the Cohen's d value with the following table:
    Effect Size Strength
    0.2 Small
    0.5 Medium
    0.8 Large

  • The carbohydrate-preworkout drink elicited a statistically significant mean increase in distance run in one hours compared to a preworkout-only drink, \(t(19) = 6.352, p < .0005, d = 1.42\).
